CSC110 Final Project Output Sheet

By Idris Tarwala and Freeman Cheng

General Overview

The dataset we used is taken from Pangaea, a data publisher for Earth and environmental studies. The data showcases the average monthly temperature in the Adda basin river area in the Central Alps. Taking the data from this area was a good choice as the temperature in the Central Alps varies throughout the year. This will allow us to make better quantitative and qualitative estimations about climate trends. In order to get a clear understanding of trends in the dataset, we have decided to use data dating back to the 1800’s. With our large scope of data, it will allow us to be more accurate with our findings and hence our results.

We determined which month was the hottest, median, and coldest on average. Our results involve these three months.

Quantitative Findings

Linear regression performed on hottest month.

The hottest month was July.

Error and Predictions

Using the first half of our July data, we can predict the second half with an average percentage error of 8.31%.

The regression predicts the average July temperature to be 14.87 °C in the year 2100.

Linear regression performed on median month.

The median month was April.

Error and Predictions

Using the first half of our April data, we can predict the second half with an average percentage error of 70.96%.

The regression predicts the average April temperature to be 4.29 °C in the year 2100.

Linear regression performed on coldest month.

The coldest month was January.

Error and Predictions

Using the first half of our January data, we can predict the second half with an average percentage error of 116.2%.

The regression predicts the average January temperature to be -2.49 °C in the year 2100.
